 the U.S. and world economies during the Depression. In four brief, clear chapters, Irwin presents an authoritative account of the politics behind Smoot-Hawley, its economic consequences, the foreign reaction it provoked, and its aftermath and legacy. Starting as a Republican ploy to win the farm vote in the 1928 election by increasing duties on agricultural imports, the tariff quickly grew into a logrolling, pork barrel free-for-all in which duties were increased all around, regardless of the interests of consumers and exporters. After Herbert Hoover signed the bill, U.S. imports fell sharply and other countries retaliated by increasing tariffs on American goods, leading U.S. exports to shrivel as well. While Smoot-Hawley was hardly responsible for the Great Depression, Irwin argues, it contributed to a decline in world trade and provoked discrimination against U.S. exports that lasted decades. Featuring a new preface by the author, Peddling Protectionism tells a fascinating story filled with valuable lessons for trade policy today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDepressionsy1929zUnited States. 0aProtectionismzUnited States. 0aTariffzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh  aA Monetary History of the United States.  aAd valorem tax.  aAggregate demand.  aAmendment.  aBalance of trade.  aBank failure.  aBusiness cycle.  aCalculation.  aCentral bank.  aCommodity.  aCompetition.  aCongressional Record.  aConsumer Goods.  aConsumer.  aConsumption (economics).  aCurrency.  aDaniel Patrick Moynihan.  aDebenture.  aDeflation.  aDepreciation.  aDisaster.  aDonald Trump.  aDuty-free shop.  aEconomic growth.  aEconomic indicator.  aEconomic nationalism.  aEconomic problem.  aEconomic recovery.  aEconomics.  aE